    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Currently, most Cython users have to implement code in their `setup.py` files to decide whether to recompile the `.pyx` sources with Cython or not, and what to do if Cython is not installed. Essentially this dance:\r\n\r\nhttp://docs.cython.org/en/latest/src/reference/compilation.html#distributing-cython-modules\r\n\r\n[PEP 517](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0517/) and [PEP 518](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0518/) provide ways to configure certain build system tools for a given project. This can be used to provide a simple Cython build package that does this once and for all, is distributed separately via PyPI, and internally calls Cython when necessary and requested, but otherwise just replaces the `.pyx` files by pre-generated `.c` files that come with the source distribution.\r\n\r\nIt would become a dependency of Cython itself and some parts of the `cythonize()` implementation would be moved into the new build package. Meaning, most of the code is already there in one way or another, just needs to be extracted and cleanly put into an external package.\r\n\r\nAlso see #1981, which could be solved at the same time (in a single package).",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I'd like to pick up the discussion off the back of the related issue #2516 here.\r\n\r\nGiven that both the suggestion here and the one raised in my issue would require extension owners to change their setup.py, I believe this gives us an opportunity to revisit the approach to how Cython extensions should be built and distributed.\r\n\r\nAs such, I would like to promote the approach highlighted in the other ticket where Cython extensions are shipped with their generated files and that those distributions are built like any other C/C++ extensions. This would allow for the setup.py to remain clear of any Cython specific parameters. The build system would only need to be more capable when the user wishes to explicitly run `cythonize` on their code.\r\n\r\nThis additional functionality would ideally be built into setuptools, for example using the setuptools_scm approach. This allows Cython to be detected and only allow `cythonize` to be invoked (perhaps through --cythonize flag to build_ext) if the Cython module exists (I believe the old cython integration into setuptools did something like this). There can also be a new argument for `setup()` which could represent `cythonize_args: {**kwargs}`. \r\n\r\nThe more difficult part about this approach is the fact that for a Cython extension to be built by distutils/setuptools without invoking cythonize, all sources must be specified as their generated filename and not their pyx one which is a shift in mindset and also potentially a non-trivial implementation which applies the reverse transition of .cpp/.c -> .pyx through source file discovery, alternatively this could be done in cythonize itself.",
